<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Convoy Experiences Sniper Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Convoy Experiences Sniper Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2404044294 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 0300 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2404044294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] This morning, following the expiry of the NATO 
ultimatum, our correspondent filed this report at about 0000 GMT. 
  Twelve minutes past midnight, two UN Protection Forces 
[UNPROFOR] armored carriers carrying Ukrainian soldiers entered 
Gorazde. They were welcomed by antiaircraft weapons fired from 
chetnik positions at the approach to the town. In the town 
center, they came across sniper fire from the hills on the right 
bank of the Drina. The rest of the convoy started entering 
Gorazde at 0145 hours. French General Soubirou, the commander 
of the Sarajevo sector [word indistinct] also arrived aboard 
this convoy. 
  No changes have been sighted at the chetnik positions. The 
snipers are still firing at the main communications and 
crossroads. At 0100 hours sharp, a large-caliber shell landed in 
the town center, followed by several explosions on the outskirts 
of the town. According to initial reports, some people were 
wounded. At 0200 hours, the chetniks on the right bank of the 
Drina were still only a few hundred meters from the hospital. 
Fahrudin Becic reporting for Bosnia-Herzegovina Radio and TV 
from Gorazde. 

</TEXT>

