<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Situation in Gorazde -- 23 April </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Situation in Gorazde -- 23 April </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    UN Convoy Arrives </H4>

<F P=102> LD2304225894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2242 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2304225894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, April 23 (TANJUG) -- The column of 
UNPROFOR combat vehicles arrived late Saturday night [23 April] 
in Gorazde, a Moslem enclave in eastern Bosnia, agencies 
reported, U.N. spokesman Maj. Guy Vinet said. UNPROFOR members 
will be deployed in the area three kilometers from the center of 
Gorazde on both banks of the River Drina, which flows through 
the town, declared a safe area a year ago by the U.N. this was 
in keeping with the agreement reached Friday in Belgrade by 
Bosnian Serb republic (R.S.) President Radovan Karadzic and 
UNPROFOR head of mission Yasushi Akashi, through the mediation 
of Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic. The Serbian forces 
around Gorazde are to withdraw to three kilometers from the town 
by Sunday at 00:01 GMT. Otherwise, as NATO council decided 
Friday, they would be exposed to NATO air strikes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

