<H3> <TI>   Silajdzic Hails Serbian Withdrawal Ultimatum </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Silajdzic Hails Serbian Withdrawal Ultimatum </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2204181994 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2204181994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Bosnia-Herzegovina Prime Minister </F>
Haris Silajdzic in unspecified location by Radio Sarajevo studio 
announcer in Sarajevo on 22 April -- live] 
  [Text] [Studio announcer] Esteemed listeneres, we have 
just been informed that we have Bosnia-Herzegovina Prime 
Minister Haris Silajdzic on the line. Good evening. 
  [Silajdzic] Good evening. 
  [Studio announcer] Mr. Silajdzic, at the beginning of the 
newscast we announced that we had received news that the NATO 
(?ambassadors) had reached a decision on a new ultimatum to the 
Serbian aggressor. We also said that we could not confirm this 
information. Can you confirm it? 
  [Silajdzic] Yes. The ultimatum to the Serbian forces calls 
for their withdrawal by midnight tomorrow [23 April] to a 
distance of three kilometers from the center of Gorazde. If 
they fail to comply, every target within a 20 km radius will be 
bombed. That is the ultimatum. 
  [Studio announcer] Could you comment on what will happen? 
Will the aggressor comply with the ultimatum? 
  [Silajdzic] That remains to be seen. If they do not comply, 
(?punishment) will follow. 
  [Studio announcer] Has this decision come too late? 
  [Silajdzic] Whether it is too late or not -- these are 
academic questions. It is too late for the dead, but it is not 
too late for the living. It is not too late for those who are 
defending themselves. Therefore, we hail this decision, and we 
hope it will be implemented. Thank you. 
  [Studio announcer] Thank you. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

