<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Deny Blocking Convoy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Deny Blocking Convoy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2504105094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1025 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2504105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, April 25 (TANJUG) -- The Bosnian Serb army 
headquarters has denied a statement by a U.N. Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) spokesman in Sarajevo to the effect that Bosnian Serb 
forces had blocked a second convoy of peacekeepers for the 
eastern Bosnian Moslem enclave of Gorazde immediately after it 
had left Sarajevo on Sunday [25 April]. The French AFP news 
agency quoted the statement on Sunday. 
  A protest note, which the Bosnian Serb army H.Q. has sent to 
UNPROFOR commands in Zagreb and Kiseljak, says that UNPROFOR on 
Sunday asked a permission for its convoy to pass through the 
Bosnian Serb territory three times and the permissions were 
invariably given them. The note quotes a statement by the 
deputy chief of UNPROFOR command for Bosnia-Herzegovina to the 
effect that the problem with the convoy was that it had not 
started from Sarajevo, because some countries, which had given 
their troops, did not agree to their leaving for Gorazde. 
  This was primarily France, the note states and adds that the 
convoy was at the airport since early morning until the 
afternoon, when its structure was finally changed. This can be 
confirmed by Captain Drole, an officer in the headquarters of 
Colonel Sonic, UNPROFOR chief of staff for Section Sarajevo, 
says the statement. 
  The Bosnian Serb army H.Q. statement says that UNPROFOR 
convoy, which should have left Sarajevo at 10 A.M. (0800 GMT), 
should have consisted of 221 troops from the British, French and 
Ukrainian contingents. However, the convoy, which entered the 
Bosnian Serb territory at 5.05 P.M., consisted of British (117 
members), Egyptian (51), Russian (20), Ukrainian (48), French 
(5) and Nordic (3 members). The note explains that added to the 
newly-formed convoy were some "new members," who had not been 
discussed earlier in the day. They were military observers and 
members of the UNPROFOR civilian affairs, UNPROFOR civilian 
police and UNICEF. 
  We have allowed that too, and the newly-formed convoy 
entered 
the territory of the Bosnian Serb republic at 5.05 P.M. and set 
out for Gorazde, says the protest note. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

