<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims, Croats Fail To Agree on President </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslims, Croats Fail To Agree on President </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2304201494 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1854 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2304201494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 23 (TANJUG) -- Delegations of 
Bosnian Croats and Moslems failed Saturday [23 April] to reach 
agreement in Sarajevo on naming the future president of the 
Moslem-Croatian Federation in Bosnia-Herzegovina. As reported 
by the Croatian radio, the deadline for reaching the agreement 
was extended until next week. The delegations headed by Bosnian 
Croatian leader Kresimir Tubak and Prime Minister of the Moslem 
Government in Sarajevo Haris Silajdzic set forth, as claimed by 
the same source, their pros and cons of the candidate for 
president, giving legal and political reasons. 
  Invoking the Washington Accord on forming Moslem-Croatian 
Federation in Bosnia, signed earlier this year under strong U.S. 
pressure, the Croatian side sought to see a Croat as head of the 
first president of the Moslem-Croatian Federation. The same 
source set out that the Croats were prepared also for a 
compromise: This post they would yield to the Moslems, but on 
condition Silajdzic be named instead of the proposed Moslem 
leader Alija Izetbegovic, whom the Croats have no wish to see 
under any circumstances heading the joint federation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

