<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Says Serbs Free Final UN Observer </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Says Serbs Free Final UN Observer </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2204183894 Paris AFP in English 1831 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2204183894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, April 22 (AFP) -- The final UN military 
observer held by Bosnian Serb forces was freed Friday afternoon 
[22 April], said UNPROFOR [United Nations Protection Force] 
spokesman Major Eric Chaperon. The observer, who was named as 
Dutch Major Van Baal, was freed along with his Serb interpreter, 
the United Nations Protection Force spokesman said. Van Baal 
informed his Sarajevo headquarters of the men's release, the 
circumstances of which were not detailed. 
  The two men went missing April 11, the day after the first 
North Atlantic Treaty Organisation air strike on Serb forces 
besieging the eastern Bosnian Moslem enclave of Gorazde. 
Fifty-eight unarmed UN military observers were placed under 
house arrest by Serb forces in areas under their control in 
reprisal for that air strike and a second strike a day later. 

</TEXT>

