<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Secure `Fair Trial' for French Aid Workers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Secure `Fair Trial' for French Aid Workers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204172894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1633 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2204172894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 22 (TANJUG) -- The Bosnian Serb Army 
investigative officials have secured the arrested eleven members 
of the French non-governmental humanitarian organizations 
Premiere Urgence a fair trial, Bosnian Serb Army Chief Command 
said Friday [22 April]. Premiere Urgence members, suspected of 
involvement in the smuggling arms for the Bosnian Moslems, have 
been given an interpreter and advised in French of their rights. 
They have also been allowed to hire a lawyer and to be visited 
by French authorities officials. The eleven Frenchmen, arrested 
at a Serb check-point in Sarajevo on April 8 charged with 
transporting arms and ammunition to Moslems. 
  The Bosnian Serb news agency SRNA said they were to stay in 
prison in the Bosnian Serb republic territory until the 
investigation was completed. The Bosnian Serb Army Chief 
Command, recalling that illegal arms and ammunition transport 
was violating the U.N. Security Council ban on arms deliveries 
to the former Yugoslavia, on Thursday disclaimed that the French 
nationals were held hostage. 

</TEXT>

