<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic Responds </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Izetbegovic Responds </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2404184794 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2404184794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Alija Izetbegovic, the president of the presidency 
of our country, today sent a letter to John Major, the prime 
minister of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern 
Ireland. In the letter, President Izetbegovic thanked Prime 
Minister Major for his letter of 21 April. I am pleased that 
the Minister of State Douglas Hogg will visit Sarajevo during 
the first week of May. We will welcome him and wish him success 
in his mission. As you suggested, during the visit we can agree 
on the date and the program of my and my prime minister's visit 
to London. I also wish to thank you for your message regarding 
the tragedy of Gorazde and for your government's active role in 
passing the latest UN and NATO resolutions. These resolutions 
have considerably alleviated the situation for the tens of 
thousands of Gorazde citizens but unfortunately peace and safety 
from Serb attacks are still far away. 
  I am glad to hear that your government shares the view that 
a 
peaceful solution to Bosnia-Herzegovina implies the withdrawal 
of Karadzic's Serbs from the considerable part of the occupied 
territories. In our view, these are the areas with the majority 
Muslim and Croatian population before the aggression, President 
Izetbegovic says in conclusion of his letter to British Prime 
Minister John Major. 

</TEXT>

