<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Negotiations Between Bosnian Croats, Muslims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Negotiations Between Bosnian Croats, Muslims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2304140594 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1300 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2304140594 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Negotiations between the delegations of the Croat 
republic of Herceg-Bosna and the Bosnia-Herzegovina Government 
have begun in Sarajevo. They are to discuss the implementation 
of the constitution of Bosnia-Herzegovina and the Washington 
agreement. Ankica Bosavljak reports: 
  [Begin Bosavljak recording] A working meeting beteen the 
Croat and Bosnian Muslim sides in Bosnia-Herzegovina began in 
Sarajevo this morning. The meeting is intended to prepare 
deputies for the upcoming session of the Assembly of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. The negotiating teams are headed by Kresimir 
Zubak, president of the presidential council of the Croat 
republic of Herceg-Bosna, and Bosnian Prime Minister Haris 
Silajdzic. The final result of today's talks should solve the 
dilemma about the election of the future president and vice 
president of the federation and the prime minister-designate of 
the federal government. Even if no names are made public, it 
will be known which nation will provide which officials. 
  In a break at 1400, Kresimir Zubak told us that during the 
first part of the meeting they discussed humanitarian and 
economic issues, and that though the talks were successful, the 
more difficult, political part of the agreement was to follow. 
Kasim Trnka, minister of justice in the Bosnian Government, was 
also optimistic in his evaluation of today's talks. He 
expressed hope that a successful agreement will be reached. 
[passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

