<DATE1>  25 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Situation in Gorazde -- 25 April </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Situation in Gorazde -- 25 April </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Serbs `Scorching the Earth' </H4>

<F P=102> AU2504084694 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 0800 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2504084694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Enes Musevic] </F>
  [Text] After 28 days and nights of the worst hell, the 
citizens of Gorazde that have survived seem to have entered 
better and quieter times. This is suggested by events since 
early this morning. The chetnik snipers, anti-aircraft weapons, 
and tanks have fallen silent. Under pressure from the 
international community and with the arrival of the first 
contingent of blue helmets, the murderers from the hills do not 
seem to live here any more. 
  The first estimates suggest that the chetniks -- despite the 
considerable delay considering the NATO deadline -- have started 
to withdraw from the points from where they have been sowing 
death in Gorazde. The chetniks are scorching the earth as they 
pull back. The members of the Ukrainian battalion that arrived 
in Gorazde on Saturday evening have started to impose a buffer 
zone in the region. The result is obvious: There is no more 
blood in the streets of Gorazde, there is no more death, 
screams, and pain. 
  After more than a month a UNHCR convoy with food and 
medicine 
managed to enter Gorazde late last night. Another humanitarian 
convoy has been announced for today for the starved and bleeding 
Gorazde. Still, the main concern of the people is today's 
resumption of the evacuation of the badly wounded from the 
Gorazde hospital. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

