<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Buha Says NATO Openly Siding With Muslims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Buha Says NATO Openly Siding With Muslims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2504124694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1210 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2504124694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 25 (TANJUG) -- NATO, issuing the 
latest ultimatum to the Bosnian Serbs, has openly taken the side 
of the Moslems, says Aleksa Buha, Bosnian Serb republic (S.R.) 
foreign minister. 
  In an interview published by the Belgrade daily POLITIKA 
EKSPRES on Monday, Buha described NATO ultimatums as "a two-way 
support which not only protects the Moslems from the Serb 
defence, but enables them to fire unobstructed at the Serb army 
and civilians." The NATO Council has threatened to launch air 
strikes against Bosnian Serbs unless they withdraw their heavy 
weapons to 20 km from the Moslem enclaves, U.N.-declared "safe 
areas" of Gorazde, Zepa, Tuzla, Bihac and Srebrenica. 
  Buha said that talks on Friday and Saturday between S.R. 
President Radovan Karadzic and U.N. chief for the former 
Yugoslavia Yasushi Akashi, with the mediation of Serbian 
President Slobodan Milosevic, had implied a promising course in 
resolving the "most difficult crisis in months." 
  Buha added: "We were well on the way to iron out the 
disputes 
with the U.N. Protection Force and furthermore, to reach an 
accord on Gorazde. But just as we have sighed with relief, a 
NATO ultimatum letter arrived and somewhat discredited the 
accord." 
  He said that NATO's unsynchronized involvement with 
additional ultimatums had created further confusion and 
primarily imposed a dilemma on who among a multitude of 
international organizations had the final say -- the United 
Nations, NATO or "a big power which has made both organizations 
its instruments." 
  Akashi and Karadzic, with Milosevic's mediation, have agreed 
on an immediate ceasefire around Gorazde. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-9383 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu080_i_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-080 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN `Satisfied' by Serb Withdrawal From Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN `Satisfied' by Serb Withdrawal From Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2604142994 Paris AFP in English 1341 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2604142994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, April 26 (AFP) -- The UN Protection Force 
said Tuesday that the Bosnian Serbs were making progress in 
withdrawing their heavy weapons from around the Moslem enclave 
of Gorazde ahead of a 0001 GMT deadline set by NATO. 
  "Generally we are satisfied with the progress that is taking 
place on the ground," said UNPROFOR spokesman Michael Williams. 
"The Bosnian Serb Army is withdrawing heavy weaponry from the 
20-kilometre exclusion zone and the general trend is positive." 
  He said that the United Nations' special representative to 
ex-Yugoslavia Yasushi Akashi had sent a letter overnight Monday 
to NATO's secretary general Manfred Woerner telling him that he 
was satisfied by the Serb progress and was hopeful that they 
would comply with the deadline. 
  Earlier in London, US Secretary of State Warren Christopher 
said that the Serbs had begun withdrawing their heavy weapons 
from around the battered enclave but not enough to avert the 
threat of NATO air strikes. "Today will be an important day. 
There has been some movement, but not enough," Christopher said 
after meeting with British counterpart Douglas Hurd. 
Christopher was to leave later Tuesday for Geneva and a meeting 
with Russian Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev. 
  As he spoke, a four-sided working group began meeting in 
London in search of long-term solutions to the Bosnian conflict. 
Hurd said Monday there would be "no hesitation" in ordering air 
strikes if Serb troops and weapons were not withdrawn beyond a 
20 kilometre (12 mile) radius from the centre of the Moslem 
enclave by 0001 GMT Wednesday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

