<H3> <TI>   Aid Convoy Reaches Enclave </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aid Convoy Reaches Enclave </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2604095094 Paris AFP in English 0938 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2604095094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 26 (AFP) -- An aid convoy which had 
been blocked by Serb forces arrived Tuesday in the Moslem 
enclave of Gorazde in eastern Bosnia, a spokeswoman for the 
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) said. 
  Spokeswoman Lyndall Sachs said the Danish convoy of 10 
trucks, carrying 90 tonnes of supplies, arrived in Gorazde 
Tuesday morning. 
  The convoy, which left Belgrade Monday morning, crossed into 
Bosnia Monday afternoon, but was stopped at a Serb checkpoint at 
Dobrun, some 30 kilometres (19 miles) from Gorazde, and sent 
back into Serbia, where it remained overnight. 
  On Tuesday Bosnian Serb authorities in Pale authorised the 
convoy to continue into Bosnia, Sachs said. 
  Two other aid convoys, both Russian, were on their way to 
Moslem enclaves in Bosnia, Sachs said. One was carrying 110 
tonnes of aid to Tuzla in northeastern Bosnia and the other, of 
14 trucks carrying 61 tonnes of supplies, was heading for 
Gorazde. 
  A UN convoy carrying some 250 peacekeeping troops arrived in 
Gorazde at 2:00 a.m. (0000 GMT) Monday, having taken 11 hours to 
make the 70-kilometre (40- mile) journey from Sarajevo. 
  It was blocked for two hours in the Sarajevo suburb of 
Lukavica by Serbs who objected to what they said were 
discrepancies in the convoy's papers. 

</TEXT>

