<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   PSL Council Views Concordat, Economy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PSL Council Views Concordat, Economy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2504092094 Warsaw NOWA EUROPA in Polish 25 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> WS2504092094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw NOWA EUROPA </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Prime Minister on Economic Growth; </F>
PSL Chief Council Session"] 
  [Text] On 23 April the Chief Council of the Polish 
Peasant Party [PSL] spoke out in favor of a treaty concluded 
between Poland and the Holy See in 1993. The council also 
expressed its conviction that the June elections to gmina [small 
administrative units] councils will be the most important 
political event that will enable the establishment of 
representative authorities for the next four years. Prime 
Minister Waldemar Pawlak informed the meeting's participants 
that the inflation level did not exceed 5 percent in the first 
quarter of this year, which means it was the lowest level in 
seven years. During the same time frame, output rose by 10 
percent. 
  The resolution states that the concordat regulates relations 
between two subjects of international law--that is, Poland and 
the Vatican--by defining general rules for cooperation between 
church and state. Aleksander Bentkowski reminded the 
participants that, in the document, both parties recognized each 
other's internal legal provisions and obliged themselves to 
respect those provisions. The resolution regarding the document 
was adopted by an overwhelming majority of votes, and it was 
also stressed that the PSL regards it as harmful to introduce 
disputes on the concordat into political campaigns and that that 
is why the council spoke in favor of an accelerated rate of 
proceedings to ratify the concordat. 
  "The economic indicators are optimistic, and, from an 
economic standpoint, the situation is quite good," the prime 
minister said. In the opinion of the government's chief, after 
an analysis of wages and salaries in the first quarter, there 
are no reasons for concern. As Pawlak reported, wages and 
salaries in March rose by about 14 percent and 8.8 percent, 
without taking into account salaries from profit [not further 
specified]. "And we should keep in mind that, in terms of time, 
March is 12 percent longer than February," the prime minister 
stressed. 
  W. Pawlak expressed his hope that talks will be initiated 
between the government and the striking miners, and that the 
problem will be solved to the employees' advantage. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-9416 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu080_p_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
