<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Crans Montana Forum </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on Crans Montana Forum </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Officials Discuss `Partnership' </H4>

<F P=102> AU2404145394 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1820 GMT 23 Apr 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2404145394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest, ROMPRES, 23/4/1994 -- "Partnership for 
Peace" [PFP] was the theme of a session held in plenum Saturday, 
23 April, afternoon, during the Bucharest conference of the 
Crans Montana Forum. 
  Chaired by Charles Thomas, ambassador in the United States 
Department of State, and by Jean-Paul Carteron, president of the 
Forum Foundation, the session occasioned a presentation of 
opinions regarding the Partnership for Peace. 
  In his address, Gheorghe Tinca, Romanian minister of 
defense, 
stressed that the Partnership for Peace was the sole initiative 
to start the evolution process that could ensure security in 
Central and Eastern Europe, while Romania's adherence was 
proving the will to integrate within European and Euro-Atlantic 
structures. 
  Approaching the political dimension of the initiative, the 
speaker stressed that the ensurance of indirect guarantees for 
security could eliminate any discrimination among states, but in 
the conditions of tempering integration at various speeds, that 
could lead to new separation marks on the continent, so that the 
security of any country should not be conceived to the detriment 
of other countries participating in the partnership. 
  In the opinion of Petre Roman, president of the Democratic 
Party (National Salvation Front), the Partnership for Peace is a 
serious step towards NATO's widening and consolidation. 
  Stressing from the very beginning on the need for security, 
Jean Freymond, director of the Geneva Center for Practical 
Studies on International Negotiations, assessed that the Eastern 
and Central European countries should not indulge in illusions 
of joining NATO, "illusions that might be turned tomorrow into 
disappointment". 
  The conclusions over the debates were however optimistic, 
the 
Partnership for Peace being viewed as a fundamental contribution 
to the security and stability, to consolidation of democratic 
structures and of the process of transition in Central and 
Eastern European states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

