<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik Discusses Nation's Place in Europe </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moravcik Discusses Nation's Place in Europe </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2204165494 Prague CTK in English 1514 GMT 22 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2204165494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava April 22 (CTK) -- Doubts about 
Slovakia's orientation towards the West, which surfaced during 
Vladimir Meciar's premiership, are unsubstantiated, Slovak 
Premier Jozef Moravcik told CTK today. 
  He said Slovakia's place in Europe was illustrated by the 
agreements the country had signed, for instance the Association 
Agreement with the European Union (EU). He reiterated that 
Slovakia was seeking EU membership. 
  Asked whether Meciar's premiership had led the West to 
rather 
overlook Slovakia in assessing countries most fit for 
integration, Moravcik said: "It's more a question of the style 
of politics and the creation of guarantees for the development 
of the institutions of parliamentary democracy. It is a 
domestic policy question, which in my view will have less and 
less importance. I wouldn't overestimate that." 
  He confirmed that cooperation within the Visegrad Group -- 
Slovakia, the Czech Republic, Poland and Hungary -- remained 
attractive for Slovakia. Its importance resided principally in 
accelerating admission to the EU. If the Group did not achieve 
that it would become senseless, he said. "I, however, am 
convinced it still is meaningful," Moravcik said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

