<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik on Preelection Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moravcik on Preelection Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2404142594 Prague CTK in English 1914 GMT 23 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2404142594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, April 23 (CTK) -- "We favour 
negotiations on the creation of pre-election blocs. However, I 
think that the forming of a political party from in the long 
term and from the viewpoint of the stabilisation of the 
political scene is more important than a pre-election campaign," 
Chairman of the Democratic Union of Slovakia (DEUS) Jozef 
Moravcik told journalists today. 
  Moravcik, who is also Slovak premier, was speaking after the 
assembly where DEUS was established through a merger between 
Moravcik's Alternative of Political Realism (APR) and the 
Alliance of Slovak Democrats (AD) of former foreign minister 
Milan Knazko. 
  Knazko, who was elected first deputy chairman, said that 
DEUS 
was oriented towards Liberal International and hoped to become a 
full- fledged member in a short time. DEUS' closest partners in 
the Czech Republic are the Free Democrats (SD) of former 
Czechoslovak Foreign Minister Jiri Dienstbier, he added. 
  Today's merger conference was attended by leading 
representatives of Slovak political parties with the exception 
of the opposition Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) and 
the Slovak National Party (SNS). The conference was also 
addressed by representatives of liberal parties from Hungary, 
Poland and Austria. 
  Moravcik said that in connection with the agreement that no 
political leaders would be represented in the coalition 
government, the DEUS statutes say that during his time in the 
government he would be represented in the leadership of DEUS by 
Knazko. 
  Asked if DEUS would adhere to the screening law while 
composing its election list of candidates, Moravcik answered 
that an amendment to the law had been initiated. This would 
concern people who were forced to sign collaboration agreements 
with the StB secret police due to their profession, though they 
did not operated in the section aimed "against domestic 
enemies". As an example, Moravcik gave workers in the arms 
industry. "If the screening law is valid, we will observe it," 
he added. 
  The screening law, adopted by the Czechoslovak Parliament in 
1991, bans people linked to the former communist-run StB secret 
police, high Communist Party officials and members of People's 
Militia from high government and economic posts until 1996. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

