<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhelev, Gligorov Comment on Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zhelev, Gligorov Comment on Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2604171094 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1600 
GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2604171094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Bulgarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Yugoslav embargo and its consequences for 
Bulgaria and Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia -- FYROM], a more rapid association of the two 
countries with European structures, and a more active 
development of economic relations between Bulgaria and Macedonia 
were the topics that Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov 
discussed with Deputy Prime Minister Evgeni Matinchev and 
National Assembly Chairman Aleksandur Yordanov today. 
  The Macedonian head of state and President Zhelyu Zhelev 
gave 
a concluding joint news conference. The historic character of 
the visit was stressed again. Here are some excerpts from the 
statements made by President Zhelev and President Gligorov 
during the news conference. 
  [Begin Zhelev recording] We established diplomatic relations 
with the Republic of Macedonia first at the level of consulates 
general and afterward at the level of a diplomatic mission, in 
other words, an embassy. Trade and economic relations have 
developed rapidly. I will allow myself to recall that at the 
beginning of 1991 trade between the two countries amounted to 
$90 million, but by 1993 it had reached $290 million. The 
dynamic and irrepressible development of trade and economic 
relations shows, among other things, that our official 
interstate relations are lagging behind the natural process of 
development. [end recording] 
  [Begin Gligorov recording, in Macedonian] I must say that we 
have had a good and serious exchange of views with the Bulgarian 
leadership on international issues and on cooperation in the 
United Nations and other international organizations, which are 
matters of common interest, and that signs of full trust and 
sincere cooperation are more and more evident. [end recording] 
  The anticipated signing of documents between Bulgaria and 
Macedonia during this first official visit by the Macedonian 
president to our country was postponed because of a language 
problem that was raised by the Macedonian side. 
  The official ceremony related to the departure of the 
Macedonian president began at the Boyana residence. The 
Macedonian head of state will depart from Bulgaria shortly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

