<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Changes in Visa Rules for UN Personnel </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Changes in Visa Rules for UN Personnel </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2604154894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1457 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2604154894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, April 26 (TANJUG) -- The Yugoslav 
Government's committee for cooperation with the U.N. Protection 
Force in the former Yugoslavia (UNPROFOR) on Tuesday said the 
U.N. peace-keepers coming from the countries with which 
Yugoslavia has agreements on the elimination of visas would not 
need visas to enter Yugoslavia as of May 15. The Yugoslav 
Government had introduced entry visas and stay permits for all 
UNPROFOR members in mid-April. The government committee for 
cooperation with UNPROFOR took the stand that the mid-April 
decision did not pertain to the above specified cases, and 
instructed the Foreign and Interior Ministries to take the 
necessary steps. 
  The Yugoslav Government also decided in mid-April that its 
prior approval would have to be obtained for the entry and 
movement of UNPROFOR transportation vehicles on Yugoslav 
territory, and that UNPROFOR personnel carriers would have to 
use only the roads designated by Yugoslav authorities. The 
committee, for its part, decided that UNPROFOR in future pay for 
all services on Yugoslav territory, including the use of 
facilities, which Yugoslavia had covered so far. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

