<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Nationwide Strike </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on Nationwide Strike </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Pol: Strike `Politically Motivated' </H4>

<F P=102> LD2704100594 Warsaw PAP in Polish 0837 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2704100594 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 27 Apr--According to Marek Pol, minister of 
industry and trade, the miners' strike is politically motivated. 
The condition for the strike to be discontinued was the 
annulment of the decision on the transformation of mines into 
holding companies. This had taken place, but the strikers had 
put forward further demands, Pol said on Polish Radio Three on 
Wednesday. 
  The industry minister stressed that he had decided to annul 
Decision No. 30 [on setting up holding companies] after talks 
with Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak, who shares his opinion that 
transformations to modernize the economy are necessary. The 
minister also hopes that the workforce in the striking mines 
will come to this conclusion. 
  Marek Pol said that it was not possible to prepare a 
schedule 
for resolving strikers' demands in 48 hours. The fulfilment of 
the demands from the mining sector by the government would mean 
that the state is being run by the trade union, and "such a 
situation is not considered normal anywhere in the world." 
  The minister blamed the union for causing the deterioration 
of moods among the miners because the unions passed on 
incomplete information to the workforce of the mines about the 
conditions for transforming the industry. According to Pol, 
information about conditions should reach each miner 
individually. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-9531 </DOCNO>
