<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Nationwide Strike </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on Nationwide Strike </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Strike `Nationwide but Not General' </H4>

<F P=102> LD2804083794 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 0700 
GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2804083794 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Maciej Jankowski, leader of Solidarity's Mazowsze 
region, who was guest of the "Sygnaly Dnia" [Signals of the Day] 
morning program on Polish Radio's First Program, said that 
today's strike is nationwide but not general because public 
services are not joining the strike. Maciej Jankowski added 
that the strike should not interrupt everyday life in towns and 
cities. 
  [Begin recording] [Jankowski] I suppose that about 1,000 
enterprises will join the strike. In Warsaw alone, all of the 
big enterprises expressed readiness and are prepared for it. 
These are: the FSO [small car plant], the Warsaw steelworks, 
Elemis, the Wola-Rawar arms enterprise, and Ursus [tractor 
enterprise], as always. 
  [Unidentified correspondent] Is this a classic strike?. 
  [Jankowski] Yes, a strike including the halting of 
production. In tens of enterprises, sirens will be sounded, 
flags displayed, and rallies organized. All large leading 
enterprises have stopped because there is no other way. [end 
recording] 
  According to Maciej Jankowski, the strike was announced 
because there was no will on the part of the government to 
implement solutions put forward by the Solidarity and approved 
by specialists. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

