Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN: Humanitarian Groups `Overstated' Victims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN: Humanitarian Groups `Overstated' Victims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2604145794 Paris AFP in English 1422 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2604145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bernard Estrade] </F>
  [Text] Sarajevo, April 26 (AFP) -- Humanitarian 
organisations overstated the number of victims caused by Bosnian 
Serb shelling of the Moslem enclave of Gorazde, UN and aid 
groups said here Tuesday. The office of the UN High 
Commissioner for Refugees [UNHCR] had earlier spoken of 715 
killed and 1,970 wounded. Of these, 600 were said to be 
seriously hurt and required immediate evacuation. But UN and 
humanitarian organisation officials here said the toll should 
probably be divided by three. The actual number of those killed 
in the three-week Serb offensive against the eastern Bosnian 
enclave was at most 250 and the number of those wounded 600 to 
700, they said. 
  Monday evening, some 200 seriously wounded patients had been 
helicoptered out of the Gorazde hospital which was now "empty", 
officials said. UNHCR spokesman Peter Kessler acknowledged on 
Tuesday that casualty figures earlier given should be "scaled 
down" and "are perhaps not all serious." Obviously embarrassed, 
he said that it was impossible for the time being to say by how 
much figures had been exaggerated. "We are in a war situation 
and in a war everybody uses propaganda," he said. "All the 
figures we gave were based on reports from our representatives 
in the field," a UNHCR official, who wished to remain anonymous, 
said. "What we did not know, and what they did not tell us, was 
that information given originated with Bosnian authorities in 
Gorazde and that they had not checked it themselves," he added. 
  The UNHCR team and that of Medecins Sans Frontieres (Doctors 
Without Borders) were in shelters and had little opportunity to 
move around town, notably during the last week. "It was the 
same for UN military observers," according to an officer at the 
headquarters of the UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR) here. The 
first doubts regarding the reported number of casualties emerged 
on Sunday when UN troops first arrived in the town after NATO 
had threatened to bomb Bosnian Serbs if they did not stop their 
bombardment and withdraw from around the city. 
  Those evacuated, according to officials here, have been 
mainly soldiers. Monday evening, a senior UNPROFOR officer was 
busy asking: "Where are the wounded? We're looking for them..." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-9546 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu082_i_94009" </HT>


