<H3> <TI>   Rose Met by Protesters </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rose Met by Protesters </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2704212594 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2000 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2704212594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] As suddenly as he had arrived in Gorazde, General 
Michael Rose, UN commander in Bosnia-Herzegovina, left the town. 
During his stay, Gen. Rose had a very brief meeting with Ferid 
Buljubasic, commander of the Bosnian Army's eastern Bosnian 
operational zone in Gorazde. After being told by the Gorazde 
commander that UN forces have not yet fulfilled their duty 
regarding the setting up of a demarcation zone 3 km from the 
town center, Gen. Rose briefly said this was not right and cut 
short the conversation. After this, Gen. Rose visited the almost 
destroyed hospital in Gorazde and the UN members in the town. 
  During Gen. Rose's stay in Gorazde, people from the nearby 
villages started gathering outside the UN headquarters. This 
protest meeting is still under way, and over 2,000 residents of 
Kazagici, Zupcici, Bare, Ugarak, Kokino Selo, [words indistinct] 
are demanding to return to their homes as soon as possible--the 
homes they left at the height of the chetnik offensive on 
Gorazde. This protest meeting--these people here--are yet 
another of many proofs that the chetniks have not withdrawn 3 km 
from the town center, because that is where the aforementioned 
villages are situated. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

